{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing and partial anomaly detection: file-level scan, metric P95/P5 for frontends, trace P95/P5 for frontend-origin traces, and focused log/error_log checks. Metric and trace analyses produced many degenerate constant-zero results that create false-positive anomalies; they are therefore not reliable here. The strongest signal is log/error_logs: all error log entries in the incident window come from frontend-0/1/2 starting at 2022-03-20 14:30:00 UTC+8, with frontend-2 having the highest count (692). log.error_count per frontend confirms per-minute errors beginning at 14:30:00. According to the workflow, we should now attempt to identify the underlying resource reason for the frontend failures using metrics that capture CPU, memory, network, and I/O behavior for the frontend pods. This step will help distinguish whether the frontend pods themselves are failing due to resource exhaustion (CPU/memory/IO) or due to network/destination failures. Because many KPIs were degenerate, we will focus only on KPI names relevant to CPU, memory, network, and filesystem/io for frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, and frontend2-0, compute global P95/P5 (from full series per rule), then inspect the incident window for directional anomalies and earliest anomaly times. The result should let us determine the most likely root cause reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "In metric.csv, restrict to cmdb_id in ['frontend-0','frontend-1','frontend-2','frontend2-0'] and to kpi_name that contain any of these case-insensitive keywords: ['cpu','memory','mem','network','net','packet','transmit','receive','error','err','fs','io','read','write','disk','throttled','file_descriptors','inodes']. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) do:\n1) Compute global P95 and global P5 using the full available series for that component-KPI (do NOT filter by incident window for percentiles).\n2) Filter rows to the incident window March 20, 2022 14:30:00 to 15:00:00 UTC+8 and compute: points_in_window, anomalies_high = count(value >= global_P95), anomalies_low = count(value <= global_P5), earliest_anomaly_high_ts (min ts or NULL), earliest_anomaly_low_ts (min ts or NULL), max_in_window, min_in_window.\nReturn a compact table limited to top 20 rows sorted by (anomalies_high+anomalies_low) desc. Include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p5, points_in_window, anomalies_high, anomalies_low, earliest_anomaly_high_ts, earliest_anomaly_low_ts, max_in_window, min_in_window. Also include a one-line summary: total anomaly points across these selected frontend resource KPIs in-window and the earliest anomaly timestamp among them (if any). Keep outputs compact; do not return raw full time series." }

{
    "analysis": "Executor's recent runs show metrics and traces are largely degenerate (many constant-zero series) and produce many false-positive anomalies with the percentile rule. The strongest, reliable signal is from logs: error_logs.csv shows repeated warning messages from frontend-0/1/2 beginning at 2022-03-20 14:30:00 UTC+8, and log.error_count confirms per-minute errors starting at that minute. Frontend-2 has the highest error count (692). However, the error message sample returned so far is truncated and generic (\"severity: warning, message: failed to retrieve...\") — we do not yet have the full message context that could point to the underlying reason (e.g., downstream service call failing, network timeout, resource exhaustion, etc.). According to the diagnosis workflow, logs are necessary to identify the root cause reason when metrics are ambiguous. Therefore we should retrieve full error log message text and a few earliest message samples per frontend (especially frontend-2) in the first minutes of the incident to read the exact failure text and determine whether the failure is application-level (failed downstream calls), network-related, or resource-related. This step is needed before we can confidently declare the root cause component, exact occurrence time, and underlying reason.",
